{"id":238879801,"title":"Clustering Based on a Multilayer Mixture Model","authors":["Jia li"],"_abstract":"In model-based clustering, the density of each cluster is usually assumed to be a certain basic parametric distribution, for example, the normal distribution. In practice, it is often difficult to decide which parametric distribution is suitable to characterize a cluster, especially for multivariate data. Moreover, the densities of individual clusters may be multimodal themselves, and therefore cannot be accurately modeled by basic parametric distributions. This article explores a clustering approach that models each cluster by a mixture of normals. The resulting overall model is a multilayer mixture of normals. Algorithms to estimate the model and perform clustering are developed based on the classification maximum likelihood (CML) and mixture maximum likelihood (MML) criteria. BIC and ICL-BIC are examined for choosing the number of normal components per cluster. Experiments on both simulated and real data are presented.","cited_in":[{"id":268525648,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/268525648_Functional_clustering_in_nested_designs_Modeling_variability_in_reproductive_epidemiology_studies"},{"id":227859789,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227859789_Hidden_Markov_Models_with_mixtures_as_emission_distributions"},{"id":254951479,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/254951479_Performance_of_Bayesian_Model_Selection_Criteria_for_Gaussian_Mixture_Models_1"},{"id":41693678,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/41693678_Selection_de_modele_pour_la_classification_non_supervisee_Choix_du_nombre_de_classes"},{"id":226330159,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/226330159_On_a_Multivalued_Version_of_the_Sharkovskii_Theorem_and_Its_Application_to_Differential_Inclusions_II"},{"id":229901217,"url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229901217_SMIXTURE_Strategy_for_mixture_model_clustering_of_multivariate_imag